ğŸ¯ SKILLS MASTERED
1. Data Quality & Cleaning (Phase 1-2)
What we learned:

How to audit raw data systematically
Identifying 10 types of data errors (blanks, negatives, case inconsistencies, trailing spaces, wrong calculations, duplicates)
The philosophy: Flag, don't fill â€” preserve data integrity
Regional Excel settings (German vs US: comma vs period decimals, semicolon vs comma in formulas)

Techniques applied:

TRIM() function for removing spaces
Find & Replace for format standardization
LEN() for detecting invisible characters
IF/OR wrapper for preventing formula errors
Paste Special â†’ Values Only workflow

Key decision: Created separate Cleaned_Data sheet instead of editing raw data â€” maintains audit trail

2. Formula Engineering (Phase 3)
Functions mastered:
FunctionUse CaseExample LocationSUMAggregate totalsKPI_Engine!B5AVERAGEMean calculationsKPI_Engine!B7COUNTACount non-blanksKPI_Engine!B8SUMIFConditional sum (1 criterion)KPI_Engine!B13COUNTIFConditional countKPI_Engine!E13SUMIFSConditional sum (2+ criteria)Pivot_Analysis!B4INDEX/MATCHDynamic lookupsKPI_Engine!B19IFERRORError handlingKPI_Engine!D30AVERAGEIFConditional averageDashboard!C51
Advanced concepts:

Cross-sheet references: =Cleaned_Data!H:H
Mixed cell references: $A4 (lock column), B$3 (lock row)
Modular design: =B5/B8 instead of recalculating
Error handling: =IFERROR(B25/C25;"N/A")

Formula design philosophy:

Build calculations in layers (inputs â†’ logic â†’ outputs)
Reference cells, don't hardcode values
One formula, copy everywhere (use relative references)


3. Conditional Analysis (Phase 3)
SUMIF Pattern:
excel=SUMIF(range_to_check; criteria; sum_range)
=SUMIF(Cleaned_Data!D:D; A13; Cleaned_Data!H:H)
Meaning: "Sum all revenue where region matches cell A13"
SUMIFS Pattern:
excel=SUMIFS(sum_range; criteria_range1; criteria1; criteria_range2; criteria2)
=SUMIFS(Cleaned_Data!H:H; Cleaned_Data!D:D; $A4; Cleaned_Data!E:E; B$3)
Meaning: "Sum revenue where region = row header AND product = column header"
Why this matters: This is how Pivot Tables work under the hood. You now understand the logic.

4. Advanced Lookups (Phase 3)
INDEX/MATCH vs VLOOKUP:
FeatureVLOOKUPINDEX/MATCHDirectionLeft-to-right onlyAny directionColumn referenceNumber (breaks if columns inserted)Range (dynamic)SpeedSlower on large dataFasterInterview perceptionBeginnerIntermediate+
Our implementation:
excel=INDEX(A13:A16; MATCH(MAX(B13:B16); B13:B16; 0))
```
**Breakdown:**
1. `MAX(B13:B16)` â†’ finds highest revenue value
2. `MATCH(value, range, 0)` â†’ returns position of that value (e.g., 2)
3. `INDEX(range, 2)` â†’ returns the item at position 2 (e.g., "South")

**Interview answer:** "I use INDEX/MATCH because it's more flexible than VLOOKUP â€” works bidirectionally, doesn't break when columns change, and performs better at scale."

