## **ğŸ’¼ INTERVIEW-READY TALKING POINTS**

### **"Walk me through a data project you've worked on."**

*"I built a sales analytics dashboard in Excel using a realistic dataset with intentional quality issues. The project had three architectural layers: raw data preservation, a calculation engine, and an executive dashboard.*

*I started by auditing the raw data and documenting 10 different error types â€” missing values, negative prices, text inconsistencies, trailing spaces. Instead of just fixing them, I implemented a flagging system that maintains data integrity while documenting issues for stakeholders.*

*The calculation engine uses 40+ formulas including SUMIF for regional segmentation, INDEX/MATCH for dynamic lookups, and SUMIFS for cross-tabulation analysis. Everything is modular â€” calculations reference other cells rather than hardcoding values, so changes propagate automatically.*

*The dashboard includes KPI cards, conditional formatting to highlight outliers, and auto-updating charts. The whole system is production-ready â€” when source data changes, everything recalculates in real-time."*

---

### **"How do you handle missing data?"**

*"I follow the principle: flag, don't fill. Instead of imputing averages or deleting rows, I leave cells blank and document the issue in a notes column. For example, when Units Sold was missing, I added 'MISSING: Units Sold' to the notes and used IF/OR wrappers in formulas to prevent errors. This preserves data quality and lets business stakeholders decide whether to track down real values or exclude from analysis. Inventing data creates downstream errors that are impossible to trace."*

---

### **"What's the difference between VLOOKUP and INDEX/MATCH?"**

*"VLOOKUP can only search left-to-right and uses column numbers that break when you insert columns. INDEX/MATCH works bidirectionally, references actual ranges instead of numbers, and is more maintainable in production environments where data structures change. It's also faster on large datasets because INDEX doesn't scan the entire table."*

---

### **"How did you handle regional Excel format differences?"**

*"I worked in German Excel which uses commas for decimals and semicolons for function separators, opposite of US Excel. This caused formula errors initially â€” `=SUM(A1,A2)` had to become `=SUM(A1;A2)`, and 4.2 had to be written as 4,2. I learned to always check number alignment (right = number, left = text) and use Find & Replace to standardize decimal formats when importing data. This is critical for international teams where the same file breaks across different regional settings."*

---
